# Codex Adversarial Review

Target: branch diff against fd9f27c9d03fcab515797a818f32eaf45c2169c3
Verdict: needs-attention

No ship: the added PR-triage config is not wired into the daemon, and the prompt's primary and fallback delivery paths have concrete failure modes.

Findings:
- [critical] Cron config is inert because nothing registers it (runtime/agents/pr-triage/crons.json:3-7)
  `crons.json` declares the daily schedule, wake check, prompt, and concurrency limit, but the production daemon only loads `runtime/daemon-config.json` agents and persisted state; repository search shows `registerCron` is only called in tests and no production code discovers `runtime/agents/*/crons.json`. Inference: this PR-triage agent will never fire in production, so the feature silently does nothing.
  Recommendation: Wire daemon startup to discover these per-agent cron files and call `CronScheduler.registerCron`/`start`, or put this cron into an existing loaded daemon config path with an integration test proving a task is emitted.
- [high] Telegram MarkdownV2 payload is malformed by construction (runtime/agents/pr-triage/prompt-template.md:50-64)
  The required summary shape emits Markdown-style headings and list bullets (`#`, `##`, `-`) while the POST forces `parse_mode=MarkdownV2`. The escaping rule later only tells the agent to escape PR titles and URLs, but Telegram MarkdownV2 also reserves these structural characters. A normal non-empty summary can be rejected with HTTP 400 before the user ever receives the daily triage.
  Recommendation: Either use plain text/HTML, or specify and test escaping for the entire rendered message, including headings, bullets, counters, dates, author names, and truncation text.
- [high] Fallback alert files are incompatible with the polling loop (runtime/agents/pr-triage/prompt-template.md:97-104)
  The prompt tells the agent to write fallback files containing only `ndjsonAlert` and `details`, but `AgentManager.processPendingTask` requires every `tasks/pending/*.json` file to contain a string `agentId`; otherwise it moves the file to `tasks/poisoned` as `missing-agent-id`. The claimed `pr-triage-telegram-send-failed`/`double-failure` telemetry path will not run, hiding exactly the delivery failures it is supposed to surface.
  Recommendation: Define a real alert envelope that the daemon supports, or extend the polling loop to handle `ndjsonAlert` files before deploying this fallback path; add a test that a failed Telegram POST emits the intended telemetry.
- [medium] Classification asks for fields the command never fetches (runtime/agents/pr-triage/prompt-template.md:24-28)
  The PR list command requests `number,title,url,author,reviewDecision,statusCheckRollup,createdAt,updatedAt`, but the `waiting_claude` rule depends on PR body content and labels. Any PR with `@claude` only in the body or only the `claude-review-requested` label will be misclassified or dropped, so the summary can miss actionable Claude-owned PRs.
  Recommendation: Include `body` and `labels` in the `--json` fields, or change the bucket rules to use only fetched data and add a fixture covering a label-only Claude PR.

